      %button.btn.btn-default.btn-lg{:disabled => "disabled"}
        Big Disabled Button

.double-padded.border-regular-light-gray
  %h4 Accessibility
  %ul
    %li Buttons should display a visible focus state when users tab to them.
    %li 
      Avoid using
      %code
        :escaped
          <div> 
      or 
      %code
        :escaped
          <img>
      tags to create buttons. Screen readers don't automatically know either is a usable button.
    %li When styling links to look like buttons, remember that screen readers handle links slightly differently than they do buttons. Pressing the Space key triggers a button, but pressing the Enter key triggers a link.
    %li 
      if the 
      %code
        :escaped
          <a>
      elements are used to act as buttons – triggering in-page functionality, rather than navigating to another document or section within the current page – they should also be given an appropriate
      %code
        role="button"
      %span .



%h2.double-gap-top Text Input
%i Text inputs allow people to enter any combination of letters, numbers, or symbols of their choosing (unless otherwise restricted). Text input boxes can span single or multiple lines.
.gap-top.double-padded.border-regular-light-gray
  %label.no-gap{:for => "input-type-text"} Text input label
  %input#input-type-text{:name => "input-type-text", :type => "text"}

  %label{:for => "first-name"}
    Required text field
    %span.additional_text Required
  %input#first-name{"aria-required" => "true", :name => "first-name", :required => "", :type => "text"}/

  .input-error
    %label.input-error-label{:for => "input-error"} Text input error
    %span#input-error-message.input-error-message{:role => "alert"} Helpful error message
    %input#input-error{"aria-describedby" => "input-error-message", :name => "input-error", :type => "text"}

  %label{:for => "input-type-textarea"} Text area label
  %textarea#input-type-textarea{:name => "input-type-textarea"}

%pre
  %code
    :preserve
      %label{:for => "input-type-text"} Text input label
      %input#input-type-text{:name => "input-type-text", :type => "text"}

      %label{:for => "first-name"}
        Required text field
        %span.additional_text Required
      %input#first-name{"aria-required" => "true", :name => "first-name", :required => "", :type => "text"}/

      .input-error
        %label.input-error-label{:for => "input-error"} Text input error
        %span#input-error-message.input-error-message{:role => "alert"} Helpful error message
        %input#input-error{"aria-describedby" => "input-error-message", :name => "input-error", :type => "text"}

      %label{:for => "input-type-textarea"} Text area label
      %textarea#input-type-textarea{:name => "input-type-textarea"}

.double-padded.border-regular-light-gray
  %h4 Accessibility
  %ul
    %li 
      Avoid placeholder text for accessibility reasons. Most browsers’ default rendering of placeholder text does not provide a high enough contrast ratio.
    %li 
      Avoid breaking numbers with distinct sections (such as phone numbers, Social Security Numbers, or credit card numbers) into separate input fields. For example, use one input for phone number, not three (one for area code, one for local code, and one for number). Each field needs to be labeled for a screen reader and the labels for fields broken into segments are often not meaningful.


%h2.double-gap-top Dropdown
%i A dropdown allows users to select one option from a list.
.gap-top.double-padded.border-regular-light-gray
  %form.form
    %label.no-gap{:for => "options"} Dropdown label
    %select#options{:name => "options"}
      %option{:value => "value1"} Option A
      %option{:value => "value2"} Option B
      %option{:value => "value3"} Option C
%pre
  %code
    :preserve
      %form.form
        %label{:for => "options"} Dropdown label
        %select#options{:name => "options"}
          %option{:value => "value1"} Option A
          %option{:value => "value2"} Option B
          %option{:value => "value3"} Option C

.double-padded.border-regular-light-gray
  %h4 Accessibility
  %ul
    %li Make sure your dropdown has a label. Don’t replace it with the default menu option (for example, removing the “State” label and just having the dropdown read “Select a state” by default).
    %li Don’t use JavaScript to automatically submit the form (or do anything else) when an option is selected. Auto-submission disrupts screen readers because they select each option as they read them.


